ives on what it means to endure in an ecologically volatile world, Second Site provokes us to rethink long-held beliefs about the permanency of site-based art, and carries implications for how we understand artistic creation and the conservation of cultural heritage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEarthworks (Art) 0aEarthworks (Art)xConservation and restoration. 0aEarthworks (Art). 0aTime and art. 7aART / Environmental & Land Art.2bisacsh1 aWhiting, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhiting, Sarah.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073912140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069122496140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691224961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691224961/original  a978-3-11-073912-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK